# Week 3 — Hardware Foundations

## Topics Covered

### Display Technologies

* LCD displays use a backlight, liquid crystals, and RGB colour filters.
* Liquid crystals control how much light passes through each pixel.
* TN panels are fast but have weaker colour and viewing angles.
* IPS panels provide better colour accuracy and viewing angles.
* VA panels provide better contrast and darker blacks.
* OLED pixels create their own light and do not require a backlight.
* Mini-LED is still LCD technology but uses many small backlight zones.
* MicroLED uses individual inorganic light-emitting pixels.

### Display Specifications

* Pixel density is measured in pixels per inch, or PPI.
* Refresh rate is measured in hertz.
* Higher refresh rates allow the display to update more times per second.
* Resolution describes the horizontal and vertical number of pixels.
* 1080p is 1920 × 1080.
* 4K UHD is 3840 × 2160.
* Aspect ratio describes the relationship between width and height.
* sRGB is a standard colour gamut.

### Network Cabling

* Twisted-pair Ethernet cable uses twisting to reduce interference and crosstalk.
* Copper Ethernet normally supports distances up to 100 metres.
* UTP means Unshielded Twisted Pair.
* STP means Shielded Twisted Pair.
* Cat5e is commonly used for Gigabit Ethernet.
* Cat6 and Cat6A can support 10 Gigabit Ethernet at different distances.
* Plenum-rated cable is designed for air-handling spaces and produces less dangerous smoke during a fire.
* Direct-burial cable is designed for outdoor or underground installation.

### T568A and T568B

* T568A and T568B define the wire order used in Ethernet terminations.
* The orange and green pairs change positions.
* The blue and brown pairs stay in the same positions.
* The same wiring standard should normally be used at both ends.

### Fibre-Optic Cabling

* Fibre carries information using light instead of electrical signals.
* The core carries the light.
* The cladding keeps the light inside the core.
* Single-mode fibre uses one narrow light path and supports long distances.
* Multimode fibre supports multiple light paths and is commonly used over shorter distances.

### Patch Panels and Punch-Down Connections

* Permanent building Ethernet cables terminate at patch panels.
* Short patch cables connect the patch panel to a switch.
* Patch panels organise and simplify cable management.
* Punch-down tools terminate wires into patch panels and keystone jacks.

### Peripheral Cables

* USB means Universal Serial Bus.
* USB 2.0 supports 480 Mbps.
* USB 3.0 supports 5 Gbps.
* USB-C describes the connector shape and does not guarantee a specific speed.
* RS-232 is an older serial communication standard.
* Console cables provide direct access to routers, switches, and firewalls.
* Thunderbolt 3 uses USB-C and supports 40 Gbps.
* Daisy chaining connects multiple devices through one another.

### Video Connections

* HDMI carries audio and video.
* DisplayPort carries audio and video.
* DVI normally carries video.
* VGA carries analogue video.
* An adapter changes the physical connector while keeping a compatible signal.
* A converter changes one signal type into another.

### Storage Connections and Devices

* SATA data connects a drive to the motherboard.
* SATA power connects the drive to the power supply.
* M.2 is a physical form factor and interface.
* NVMe is a storage protocol that uses PCIe.
* AHCI means Advanced Host Controller Interface.
* SAS means Serial Attached SCSI.
* EEPROM means Electrically Erasable Programmable Read-Only Memory.
* Non-volatile storage keeps data without power.
* HDDs use spinning magnetic platters.
* SSDs have no moving parts.

### RAM

* RAM stores active data and instructions temporarily.
* RAM is volatile and loses its contents when power is removed.
* DIMMs are commonly used in desktop computers.
* SO-DIMMs are smaller and commonly used in laptops.
* DDR means Double Data Rate.
* Dual-channel memory increases memory throughput.
* When RAM becomes full, the operating system uses slower storage as virtual memory.

